{"/service/ndnp/in/batch_in_fontaine_ver01/data/sn87055779/00517016688/1927040401/0477.xml":{"full_text":"BUSINESS OUTLOOK\nIS PROMISING AS\nEASTER DAY NEARS\nIrregularity is Noted in\nWeek's Closing Lists; Steel\nContinues Advance.\nBy ELMER C. WALZElt,\nUnited News Financial Editor.\nNEW YORK, April 3.\u2014Marked\nirregularity was noted in the week\u2019s\nclosing list with leading issues ehow\u00bb\ning sharp advances and some of the\nweaker shares indicating further de\npreciation. IT. S. Steel was the out\nstanding feature of the week, rising\nto new high ground at 1 70 3-S and\nclosing the six days at 109, up\n4 1-4 points for the period and\n15 1-2 points higher than Us low\nof the year made on Jan. 28.\nThe business outlook was more\npromising as Easter approached.\nSteel business was at a high level,\nautomobile production was improv\ning and building picking up. With\nbetter weather conditions, retail\ntrade was progressing and the\nweather factor boosted the crop\noutlook, and at the same time\nbrought a decline in the markets for\nwheat and cotton.\nUUyillg hi sicei wi iJiutiioo\noarly on the assumption that an\nextra dividend would be declared\nHowever, when Judge Albert H.\nGary, chairman of the steel corpora\ntion, spiked this rumor as incorrect,\ninsofar as a discussion of an extra\nwas concerned, the price continued\nto advance, showing the gain baked\non something less ethereal\u2014profits of\nthe company which are expected to\nrun high in the first quarter. Sell\ning on Saturday was based to some\nextent on the prospects of a further\ndecrease in .tonnage in the state\nment for March to be issued next\nSaturday.\nKails Best.\nKails presented the best picture as\na group in the entire market. A\nsetback was given this section as a\nresult of the St. Louis and O'Fallon\nrailroad decision on the interstate\ncommerce commission, ordering the\nroad to pay to the government some\n$280,000 excess profits. The basis of\nvaluation in the decision was the fu\nture of 1914, and it will be from this\nhngle that the case will be brought\n.before the Supreme court for adjust\nment. Prospects that the Supreme\ncourt would reverse the I. C. C.,\nfinding dissipated the break, and\nbuying activities were resumed.\nChicago, Rock Islard and Pacific\nmade one of the best gains in the\ncarrier section, raising its price 5 7-8\npoints for the week. Erie shot up to\nnew high ground on news that the\ncompany planned to spend $25,000,\n000 for improvcmcols. Colorado\nSouthern rose 7 1-4, Kansas City\nSouthern 4 3-8, Bangor Aroostook\n6 1-2 Missouri Pacific 6 3-8, Texas\nPacific 3 5-8\u201e Western Maryland\n6 5-8 and Western Maryland second\npreferred 7 1-8.\nBaking Shares Drop.\nBaking shares were hard hit in the\nIndustrial section. Continental Bak\ning A losing 7 5-S, and the pre\nferred losing 8 1-2, while Ward A\nwas depressed S points. American\nTelephone and Telegraph lost nearly\ntwo points, American Smelting, 3 1-4,\nAmerican Woolen, 2 1-2, and Cali\nfornia Packing 4. Oils were gener\nally lower, General Asphalt pre\nferred, losing the heaviest, off 13\npoints\nInternational Silver made the wid\nest forward movement, jumping\n22 1-2 points. Colorado Fuel wras\nup 7 3-4, DuPont 9 7-8, Woohvorth\n6 1-4, Coca-Cola 4 7-8 and Com\nw mercial Solvents B 5 1-2, Insurance\nissues spurted. Continental Insurance\ngaining 10 points, Fidelity-Phoenix\n6 points and Roesia, 5,\n/ftrf&ll \u2018DT&WlHl'S\nMBS. MARY E. GALEENER\nMrs. Mary E. Galeener, 72, a resi\ndent of St. Joseph county during her\nentire life, died at 10:25 o'clock Sat\nurday night, following an illness of\nseveral years, at her residence on\nR, R. No. 3.\nMrs. Galeener was born Aug. ^6,\n1855 in St. Joseph county, and was\nmarried in 1876 to David N. Galeen\ner in Buchanan, Mich.\nShe is survived by her husband,\ntwo sons, Clarence and Clyde N.\nGaleener, South Bend; three grand\ncihildren; three sisters, Mrs. Louisa\nAnstis, Grand Haven, Mich.; Mrs.\nMatilda DeGraf, and Mrs. Hattie\nHamond, South Bend, and a brother,\nJohn Frame, Kalamazoo, Mich.\nFuneral services will be conduct\ned at 2 o'clock Tuesday afternoon at\nthe L. H. Orvis funeral home by the\nRev. Edgar Duker, Ardmore. I^urial\nwill be in Highland cemetery.\nJAMES ALLEN\nJames Allen, 72, died at his resi\ndence in German township at 5\no'clock Sunday morning following an\nillness which lasted for one year.\nMr. Alien was born in Kosciusko\ncounty, Indiana, in March, 1855. He\ncame to German township five years\nago and has resided there since that\ntime.\nThe body may be viewed at the\nIJOlHs and Haverstock funeral chap\nel, 2528 Mishawaka avenue, until the\ntime of the funeral, which will take\nplace Tuesday afternoon from the\nfuneral chapel. Other funeral ar\nrangements have not yet been made.\nITALIAN LEAVES FOR\nHOT SPRINGS TODAY\nBy Vnltcd News:\nSAN ANTONIO. Texas. April 3.\u2014\nCommander Francesco De Pinedo.\nItalian aviator, who is making a\n80.000 miles tour of South America,\nthe United States and Europe, plans\nto take off at dawn Monday for\nElephant Butte dam, at Hot Springe,\nN. M.\nEngine trouble delayed the flyer\nSunday rnornjBp when he tried to\nrise front Meflfw* lake in his big\nplane, the Santa Marfa. De Pinedo\u2019s\nplane is equipped for landing only\nop the water and his trip from New\nOrleans to the Pacific coast, al\nthough over land, has been arranged\ngo that he can land on convenient\nlalees and rivers.\nnitrgnl with driving while in\ntoxicated. Alfred Van Hee, 33, 227\nVf. Sixth street, Mishawaka, was ar\nrtated Sunday evening in the 2600\nbl#ck. W. Division street, by Offi\ncers Hudak and Weeolek.\nLODGE NOTICES\nKt. Joseph I .Oder No. 45. F. A. U.\nStated meeting Monday. April 4, 8 p. m.\nHoward Emmons. W. M.; ft. W. Smith,\nAdv.\u201492 p. m. 94 a. iu.\na 6\nLarge Audience\nEnjoys Beautiful\nSymphony Concert\nBY JULIA M. RODE\nThe South Bend Symphony or\nchestra played a beautiful program\nto a large and enthusiastic audience\nat its eighth annual concert Sunday\nafternoon, In the high school audi\ntorium. under the able direction of\nFrederic Ingersoll.\nThe players were in fine form and\ndelighted the audience with their\nsplendid, musicianly playing and\ndisplayed a high order of technical\nskill, not often found in an organi\nzation composed so largely of stu\ndents. The program, as a whole,\nwas most satisfactory. It was built\nwith high regard for proper balance\nof contrast and color and was played\nin such a way as to make one feel\nsure each player had a most inti\nmate understanding of the demands\nof each number.\nMr. Ingersoll has worked with un\ntiring devotion and given most gen\nerously of his time and talents in\norder to obtain 6uch splendid re\nsults. It proves that he is a musi\ncian of more than ordinary attain\nment and a conductor who has great\nfeeling for dramatic values.\nMr. Russell Hendrickson of The\nChicago Symphony orchestra was\nthe soloist. He is a cellist who cer\ntainly has a message in his playing.\nHe has charm, a beautiful tone and\nwith him, the master of technical\ndifficulties is an accomplished thing.\nMiss Dora Hershenow, pianist, was\nthe efficient and artistic accompa\nnist for Mr. Hendrickson.\nThese concerts are such a contri\nbution to the musical life of the city,\nthat one looks forward to them with\ngreat pleasure. There have been\nmany expressions of regret that a\npermanent orchestra could not be\nestablished in South Bend, so that\nthese splendid concerts could be\nheard more frequently.\nTRINITY M. E. CLASS\nPRESENTS PAGEANT\nNearly 150 Persons Witness\n\u201cThe Challenge of the\nCross\u201d at Y.W.C.A.\nNearly 130 persons attended the\npageant, \u201cThe Challenge of the\nCross,\u201d given by the Triple L Sun\nday school class of the Trinity\nMethodist Episcopal church in the\nV. M. C. A., gymnasium at 4 o\u2019clock\nSunday afternoon.\nSeven persons took part In the\npageant, which portrayed the differ\nent attitudes which various people\ntake towards the bearing of their\ncrosses. Mrs. George Love, repre\nsenting \u201cEvangel,\" or the spirit of\nChristianity, interrogated the six\ndisciples as to their ideas regarding\nthe crosses they must bear.\nThe parts of the disciples were\ntaken by Mrs. Chester Wolf, Mrs.\nCharles Itomine, Mrs. Ray Williams,\nMrs. Fred Zorn, Mrs. Raymond E\nCollier and Mrs. Robert Miller.\nA musical interpretation of the\npageant was given by a quartet made\nup of Miss Kathryn Boone, Miss\nGrace Buswell, Frederick Axtell and\nClaude Davey. Miss Jessie Owens\naccompanied the quartet on the\npiano.\nRobert Helmeamp, 627 E. Bronson\nstreet, reported to police Sunday\nnight the theft of a motormeter from\nhis car, parked in the rear of the\nBlackstone theater.\nA Ford coupe was stolen Monday\nnight from its parking place, near\nMain and Madison streets, accord\ning to a report to police by the own\ner, Ralph Droud, 1751 S. Marine\nstreet.\nNoali Miller. 21, Nappanee, Ind.,\nwas arrested Sunday night at Mon\nroe and Lincolnway E. by Officer\nArt Martin on a charge of exceeding\nthe speed limit.\nDamage estimated at $100 result\ned from a fire at 12:25 Sunday aft\nernoon on the roof of a rooming\nhouse conducted by Mrs. Emma\nHunt at 334 S. Main street. The\nbuilding is owned by the St. Joseph\nLoan and Trust Co. The alarm waa\nanswered by the chemical truck\nfrom the Central fire company.\nKIAMIL BEY NAMED\nAMBASSADOR TO U. S.\nLONDON, April 3.\u2014ICiamil Bey,\ndeputy for Constantinople and for\nmer under-secretary of state for for\neign affairs in the Turkish cabinet,\nhas been appointed ambassador to\nthe United States, according to an\nexchange telegraph company\u2019s die\npatch from Constantinople. His most\nrecent diplomatic assignment was\nthat of Turkish consul general in\nBrussels.\nI\nI\nMothers and\nTheir Children\nOne Mother Says:\nMy little son enjoys building\nhouses with tho covers of boxes.\nboth round and square, using snap\nclothespins to clip on the edges of\nthem as supports. The top of an\noatmeal box with a half dozen\nclothespins, makes a pergola effect.\nA square cover will fit a larger\nbuilding. A fancy face powder box\nmakes a nice little cupola. And so\nit goes. I dipped the clothespins\ni:. green, pink and different colored\ndyes, and these, with the natural\nwooden ones, makes a pleasant\nvariety.\nNATIONS OF EUROPE\nJOIN HEATED RAGE\nFORAIRSUPREMACY\nItaly and Spain Are Stirred\nBy France\u2019s Predomin\nance On Continent\nBy ED I>. KEEN\nUnited Press Staff Correspondent\nCopyright 1927, By United Press\nLONDON, April 3.\u2014The race for\naerial supremacy continues today\nwith the countries of Europe plan\nning years ahead, while at Geneva\nthe League of Nations preparatory\ndisarmament conference has begun\ndiscussion of means whereby armed\nair forces might be limited.\nItaly and Spain have been stirred\nby France\u2019s predominance in the air\non the continent. Under-Secretary\nBalbo has announced in the Italian\nChamber of Deputies an air con\nstruction program which, by 1930,\nwould provide S63 bombing planes,\n1,250 fighting planes and C82 scout\ning planes.\nThe Spanish minister of war has\nconfirmed the statement that Spain,\nwithin 10 years, plans to have an\nair fleet of 1,400 planes, represent\ning an increase of 900. The Span\nish budget includes an appropria\ntion of 120,000,000 pesetas for the\nconstruction of planes, plus 40,000,\n000 for airdromes, machin% guns and\nother equipment.\nPoster Campaign\nThroughout Italy there is a cam\npaign to recruit young men for the\naviation service. Posters may be\nseen stressing feats of Francesco De\nPinedo, now in the United States\nafter a fliirht down the African coast.\nacross the South Atlantic, through\nSouth America, and of Commander\nXobile, who was captain of the\nXorge on its flight across the Xorth\nPole. Various slogans have been\ndevised to fire Italian youths with\nenthusiasm for flying. One of these\nis typical:\n\u201cUnder the shadow of armed\nwings lies Italy\u2019s power and safety.\u201d\nIt has been hinted that Italy\nwould spring many surprises in\nmechanics of aviation and chem\nical improvements in future war.\nItaly now has 1,123 airplanes in\nactive service.\nFrance Is Leader\nAviation authorities here say that\nFrance, with 132 squadrons of\nplanes, or approximately 1.200 first\nline machines, not counting training\nor naval planes, now is the strong\nest air power in Europe. French\nplans envisage the maintenance of\nthis supremacy. France now has\nabout 130 naval planes and plans to\nincrease the number to about 450 by\n1938.\nEngland is planning to attempt to\novertake and to continue abreast of\nFrance. England\u2019s present strength,\naccording to figures recently given\nthe dominion premiers, is 730 air\nplanes, of which about 31 squadrons\nare for home defense. By 1935,\nEngland plans to increase the- home\ndefense force to 52 squadrons, in\ncluding 13 squadrons organized on a\nterritorial (militia) basis and to in\ncrease the strength abroad in pro\nportion.\nGermany\u2019s air strength is neg\nligible because of restrictions put\nupon her by the Versailles treaty,\nbut Germany is heavily subsidizing\ncivil air lines. Russia still is weak\nbut is struggling to develop an air\nforce.\n2 SOUTH BEND GIRLS\nHONORED AT INDIANA\nSpecial to The News-Times:\nBLOOMINGTOX, Ind., April 3\nXellie Xewcomb and Helen Siniff,\nSouth Bend, are two of 33 freshmen\nco-eds at Indiana university who\nhave been chosen on the annual\nfreshman recognition list by Mortar\nBoard, senior organization. This list\nof freshmen co-eds who have shown\noutstanding ability on the campus is\nselected each year on the basis of\nscholarship, attitude and activities.\nRUSSIAN OVERSUPPLY\nBOOSTS CAVIAR SALES\nBv International News Service:\nFREXCH LICK SPRIXGS, Ind.\u2014\nAmerica\u2019s wealthy hostesses are serv\ning more caviar this year than ever\nbefore because Russia has cut the\nprice in half, Paul Perreau, western\nmanager for a Xew York imported\nfoods company declared here today.\nThe soviet regime allowed more\nRussians to fish the Caspian sea I\nsturgeon which yield caviar thus\nmaking the supply exceed the de\nmand and consequently lowering\nthe price from J14.00 a pound In\n1917 to ?7.00 in 1927, Perreau. ex\nplained.\nXew York city consumed more\ncaviar in 192C than any other Amer\nican city, with Chicago a close sec\nond, he reported.\nFERDINAND IMPROVES;\nCAROL MAY VISIT HIM\nBy United News:\nVIEXXA, April 3.\u2014King Ferdin\nand of Rumania rested better Sun\nday than at any time during the\npast week, and symptoms of grippe,\nwhich for a time caused fear for his\nlife, have almost disappeared, ac\ncording to an official statement given\nthe United Xews from Bucharest.\nThe king\u2019s temperature at noon\nWas 99.5. It reached 101.48 Satur\nday night.\nliy initea .News:\nBUCHAREST, April 3. Despite\nofficial denials reports persist that\nformer Crown Prince Carol, travel\ning incognito, already is In Belgrade\nen route to Bucharest where he\nhopes to bid farewell to King Fer\ndinand who is critically ill.\nEvery idea loses something of its\npurity when it aspires to realisation.\nPWj\nMebbe tli\u2019 fear o' muck rakin\u2019 bi\nographers \u2019ll cause a lot o\u2019 ole cod\ngers t\u2019 stay In tlier class. Radio an\nnouncers arc gettin\u2019 t\u2019 be just like\ntemporary chairmen\u2014they seent t\u2019\nfergit who 111\u2019 audience is waitin\u2019 t\u2019\nhear.\nPROSPECTS FOR TAX\nCUT STILL BRIGHT,\nOFFICIALS DECLARE\nMarch Income Levy Collec\ntions Show Unexpected\nDrop, However\nBy ROBERT S. THORNBURG\nI. N. S. Staff Correspondent\nWASHINGTON, April 3.\u2014Despite\na sudden and unexpected dropping\neft in income tax collections for\n.March, prospects for tax reduction\nin the next Congress have not been\ndimmed, high treasury officials de\nclared tonight.\nAlthough it appeared that, from\na strictly economic standpoint, Sec\nretary Mellon would prefer that the\ntax rates be left as they are, for\nat least another year, political in\nformation preceding the 192S presi\ndential election is expected to play\nan important part in a revision of\nthe revenue act.\nBess Than Estimate\nMarch collections were $613,534,\n000, a gain of about $17,000,000\nover the same month last year, but\n$65,000,000 under the March 1 es\ntimate. A jump in corporation tax\nes was responsible for the increase,\nthis class of taxpayers having paid\"\nat a one per cent higher rate than\nlast year. The corporations were\ndescribed as enjoying a year of un\nusual prosperity in 1920. For the\nfirst nine months of the fiscal year,\nincome tax collections amounted to\n$1,G49,971,000, about $220,000,000\nabove last year. It now appears that\nthe year\u2019s collection will be more\nthan $2,150,000,000. Officials thought\nit possible that the June collection\nmight be heavier because of the drop\nin March.\nUnless there is a further cut in\nreceipts, a surplus of about $300,\n000,000 on June 30, appears likely.\nThe March 31 surplus was $419,\n624,000, exceeding the same date\nlast year by $122,000,000. A consider\nable reduction in miscellaneous in\nternational revenue almost mitigated\nthe gain in income taxes. Total re\nceipts for the first nine months were\n$3,025,933,000, about $93,000,000\nahead of 1923. The government suc\nceeded in cutting ordinary expenses\n$67,000,000 in the nine months, hav\ning expendid $2,177,500,000 in that\nperiod.\nSave On Debt Cut\nMore savings were hung up in the\ndebt reduction program. The out\nstanding gross debt of $19,000,000,\n000 on March 31 was one billion less\nthan the same day last year and less\nby $150,000,000 than Feb. 2S.\nTreasury experts, viewing taxation\nfrom a strictly financial angle, said\nthat business conditions during the\npresent year, should go toward a pos\nsible reduction in rates. With an\nother prosperous year they agreed\nthat a material cut may be made\nsafely.\nPLYMOUTH\nThe 23rd District Assembly of\nthe Rebekah lodge was held Wednes\nday afternoon and evening at Ke\nwanna with more than 200 delegates\npresent at the sessions. An election\nof. district officers resulted as fol\nlows: President, Mrs. Sullivan, of\nRochester: vice president, Nettie\nHill, of Milford; secretary, Ruby\nGoodrich, of Rochester; treasurer,\nPearl Holman, of Milford. Elizabeth\n'McLaughlin, of Plymouth, was ap\npointed chaplain of the district for\nthe ensuing year.\nMembers of the lodge were present\nfrom Akron, Argos, Bourbon, Mt.\nLebanon, Bethany, Kewanna, Leiters\nFord, Mentone, Milford, Plymouth,\nRochester, Warsaw and Claypool.\nThe next district meeting will be\nheld at Warsaw, Oct. 11, 3 927.\nCO-ED \u201cPRAYED HER\nBUNIONS OFF FEET\u201d\nBv Vnitod Nows:\nCHICAGO, April 3. Robert L.\n\u25a0Williams, graduate student at North\nwestern university, fought material\nfor a thesis: \u201cThe College Student\nand Prayer,\u201d and sent out a religiuos\nquestionnaire. There were many rea\nsons why students prayed, among\nthem being to pass exams, luck in\nlove, to earn enough money to pay\nfor college expenses, and cure from\ndisease. One co-ed wrote that she\nhad \u201cprayed bunions off her feet.\u201d\nWhat Do You Know About Music,\nHistory and Literature? Try Your\nHand at Answering These Five\nFriday\u2019s list of \u201cAsk Mr Anotliers\u201d was not so difficult. Today\u2019s,\nhowever, is different. Confidentially, tlie contest editor would have had\nto refer to the encyclopedia for the answers to three of the five, liad\nthey not accompanied the qnestions.\nRead this list and guess which three they were. Hie answers will he\nfound on page 15.\n1. What Australian opera singer adopted and adapted the name of\nher birthplace as her pseudonym?\n2. What have the following In common: Justinian, Vespasian, Diocle\ntian. Hadrian, Trajan?\n3. Who Is Robert Frost?\n4. Wliat is Sorbonnc?\n5. Where are the following burled: (a) Washington, (b) Lincoln,\n(c) Grant?\nfo. S. REFUSES TO\nADOPT PUNITIVE\nPOLICY IN ORIENT\nAppeals for Action Ignored\nBecause Course is \u201cDan\ngerous, Ineffective\u201d.\n(Continued from Page One)\nreaching the state department tn tne\nlast fen- days from influential Ameri\ncans in China, including Sterling\nlessenden, American head of the\nShanghai municipal council. Great\nBritain wante such action. One pro\nposal is that the United States use\nts warships in China to lay down an\nallied blockade of the Yangtze. The\nShanghai chamber of commerce has\njust made an appeal to Washington.\nOppose Drastic Course\nSecretary of State Kellogg has\nI said the United States is co-operat\nj ing with other governments in pro\ntecting lives and property. He is re\nluctant to go farther, although it\nmay be done if pressure grows.\nHowever, there is considerable op\nposition to a drastic course. Opposi\ntion comes, for instance, frdm such\na close administration organ as the\nWashington Post. Owned by E. B.\nMcLean, the Post\u2019s opposition is all\nthe more significant in- view of the\ntact that it has been demanding a\nstrong policy in Mexico and has re\np_eatedly, throughout the Mexican\nand Nicaraguan troubles, accurately\nforecast the state department\u2019s\nactions.\nDangerous and Ineffective\n\u201cDiscreet handling of the contro\nversy arising from the Nanking in\ncident is called for,\u201d the Post said\neditorially Sunday. \u201cWhen a respon\nsible government shall have been\nestablished in China the Nanking\ncontroversy can be adjusted.\n\u201cThe only safe and effective policy\nfor the United States to pursue at\nthis juncture is that of protecting\nAmerican -citizens on the Chinese\nseaboard. The sending of forces in\nland would be both dangerous and\nineffective.\nChina\u2019s War\n\u201cWhen Americans are aroused by\nreports of aggressions against their\nfellow citizens in China, it is well\nfor them to consider the whole sit\nuation. And not merely the fact\nthat Americans are injured. China is\nin the convulsion of civil war. It is\nChina\u2019s war. Foreign nations have\nno right to intermeddle with it.\u201d\nOn the other hand, American mis\nsionaries and business men in China\nfeel entitled to some protection from\ntheir home government. The mis\nsionaries are less insistent upon it\nthan the business men. Yet even\nwhen missionaries remain in the in\nterior in face of warnings by Ameri\ncan officials and are murdered, this\ngovernment feels an obligation.\nAnnouncement Looms\nBusiness men who have invested\ntheir capital in China demand pro\ntection as oil men are demanding It\nin Mexico. At Shanghai foreigners\nhave built up a huge modern city of\na million and a half people, the\ngreatest city in China. They do not\nwant to hand it over to the Chinese\nnationalists. They built it out of a\nmarshy waste and they want, natur\nally, to keep it. This government\nwould be severely criticized if it ask\ned them to abandon it as the na\ntionalists :demand.\n-This is-the dilemma- the .adminis\ntration is in. So far a showdown has\nbeen avoided. But Great Britain is\ngrowing increasingly impatient and\nit will be invpossible for the United\nStates to delay announcement of a\npolicy, much longer.\ny; GOSHEN\nPlans have been- completed for\nthe opening of tho annual North In\ndiana conference of the Methodist\nEpiscopal church Tuesday evening.\nBetween 600 and 700 ministerial and\nlay delegates will be in Goshen for\nthe conference, which will continue\nuntil April 11. Members of all\nchurches in the city will entertain\nthe visitors in their homes during\nthe week. The First church, where\nmost of the conference sessions will\nbe held, has been redecorated and\nthe new church community building\nis practically completed.\nThe conference will be opened\nformally Tuesday evening, when Sen\nator Arthur R. Robinson will speak.\nThe conference program proper will'\nbegin Wednesday morning. Assign\nment of pastors will not be made un\ntil the last day.\nMrs. Lydia Reynolds, 78, died at\nthe home of her son, R. A. Reynolds,\nin New Paris, Friday evening, of\nparalysis. Mrs. Reynolds came to\nGoshen with her parents, Mr. and\nMrs. Allen Smith, when she was a\nyoung girl. After her marriage to\nCharles C. Reynolds, she moved to\nMilford, where Mr. Reynolds was a\ndruggist for many years. During the\npost 20 years she had lived with her\nson in New Paris.1 Surviving are\nher son and two grandchildfen.\nFuneral services were held Mon\nday afternoon at 2:30 o\u2019clock at the\nReynolds home, and burial was at\nMilford.\nThe Goshen post of the American\nLegion will give a free trip to the\nParis convention to one of its mem\nbers at a dinner, April 15. Thirty\nfive members of the post, who have\nqualified through attendance at le\ngion meetings, will draw for the\nprize. The winner will be given ?400\nby the post to attend the convention\nin Paris next September.\nAUGUST IS BORN TO\nMAY AND DECEMBER\nBy United News:\nPLA1XFIELD. X. J., April 3\nMay and December can enjoy mari\ntal bliss, if there comes a little Au\ngust.\nWhen August X. Laggren, at the\nage of 55, married his adopted\n.laughter, Alice Amelia, Banta, who\nwas 15, the neighbors cluck-clucked\nand the \"condensed newspaper\u201d\ncameras click-clicked. But the weal\nthy awning manufacturer and his\nchild-wife fooled them all.\nAugust, jr., seven pounds, is part\nof the secret of success, according to\nLaggren and his bride.\nSPEAKS TO WOMAN AT\nDANCE AND IS KILLED\nCHICAGO, April 3.\u2014A slighting\nremark to a woman on a dance floor\nSunday precipitated a fight which\nresulted in the death of Qeorge Jack,\n23, who was accused of insulting\nMrs. Lillian Quinn, 28. According to\nC. P. Townsend, he. Jack and three\nothers were on a slumming party.\nThey went to a cafe and, as Jack\npassed Mrs. Quinn, she shouted she\nwas insulted. A free-for-all began\nand Jack was shot to death.\nPagliacci\" tc\nBe Broadcast by\nChain of Stations\nStation WSBT, South Bend, has its\nusual feature program to offer Mon'\nday night. At 7:45 o\u2019clock, a pro\ngram that will continue for tw<\nhours and 15 minutes will go on th<\nair. On this program will he Lois\nTrowbridge and her Entertainers\nRobert \u201cRed\u201d O\u2019Brien and his fanv\nous \u201cuke.\u201d from the Red Apple clul\nof Station WCX, Detroit; Ray Wit'\nner, baritone, and his accompanist\nJohnny Raybuck; \"Willis Engel, ten\nor; Clarence Harding, program di\nrector of Station WSBT, in a numbei\nof piano selections; and C. H\nBarnes, Boy Scout executive in a five\nminute talk on \u201cTimely Tips to Mot.\norists.\u201d At midnight a two hour pro\ngram by the Blackstone Kite Owl!\nwill begin. Rose\u2019s Midgets and th<\nBlackstone Syncopators, under tin\ndirection of Bob Helcamp, jwill bi\nthe features.\n\u201cI Pagliacci,\u201d the famous opera bj\nLeoncavallo, will be given by the Na\ntional Grand Opera company tonigh\nat 9 o\u2019clock, Central time, under th<\ndirection of Cesare Sodero. It wil\nbe heard through Station WEAF\nNew York; WJAR, Providence\nWTAG, Worcester; WLIT, Phiiadel\nphia; WRC, Washington; WCSH\nPortland; H CAii, Pittsburgh; wsai\nCincinnati; KSD, St, Louis; WDAF\nKansas City, and WTIC, Hartford\nEarlier in the evening, at 7:li\no\u2019clock, Strickland Gillilan, one o:\nAmerica\u2019s noted humorists, and au\nthor of the famous, \"On Agin, Of)\nAgin, Gone Agin, Finnegan,\u201d will bt\nheard from Stations WEAF, WLIT\nKSD and WSAI.\n\"The Old Home Town\u201d is the titlt\nof a radio musical presentation to b\u00ab\ngiven tonight from Station WSB, At\nlanta, at S o\u2019clock, Central time.\nThe dramatic society of Statior\nWPG, Atlanta City, will present Syd\nney Gundy\u2019s \"In Honor Bound\u201d from\nthat station tonight at 9 o\u2019clock\nCentral time. Following this pro\ngram, the elaborate celebration\nmarking the opening of the $1,000,\n000 pier will go on.\n_____\nA folk song program by the Mey\ner Davis orchestra will be on the air\ntonight from Station KTHS, Hoi\nSprings, Ark., beginning at 9 o\u2019clock,\nCentral time.\nThornton W. Burgess, noted writ\ner on animal life, will give a talk\nat 7 o\u2019clock, Central time, tonight\nfrom Station WHAM, Rochester, un\nder the auspices of the Humane so\nciety, as part of its \"Be Kind to\nAninfels\u201d week.\n\u201cRadio Play Xiglit\u201d will be the\nprogram from Station WFAA, Dal\nlas, tonight, beginning at S: 3 0\no\u2019clock, Central time. One of the\nfeatures will be La Mariquita and\nher Castilian orchestra.\nTroy\u2019s prize American Legion band\nwill give a sample of its ability to\nnight with a concert at 10 o\u2019clock.\nCentral time, from Station WIIAZ\nof Xew Tork city. x\nStudents ahd faculty of the Uni\nversity of Minnesota will take part\nin the weekly program sponsored by\nthat institution which will go on\nthe air at 8 o'clock, Central time, to\nnight from Station WCCO, Minneap\nolis-St. Paul.\nMichael Murphy, who spends his\ndays dishing out the necessities of\nlife to residents of Xew Britain,\nConn., from his grocery store, will\ndemonstrate the musical side of his\nlife tonight when he returns to the\nmicrophone at Station WTIC, Hart\nford, Conn., with a program of old\ntime \"fiddlin\u2019.\u201d He will be heard at\n6:15 o\u2019clock, Central time.\nBert Wilburn\u2019s \"Blue Moon Enter\ntainers\u201d from Wichita Falls, Tex.,\nwill hit the trail for Fort Worth to\nnight, to go' on the air from Sta\ntion WBAP of the latter city with\na novel program beginning at 9:30\no\u2019clock, Central time.\nDouglas Stanbury, who spent all\nof last season as a member of the\nChicago Civic Opera company, will\nbe one of the featured entertainers\non the program given tonight at\n6:30 o\u2019clock, Cefitral time, by Roxy\nand hi* gang from Stations WJZ,\nNew Tork; W B Z, Springfield;\nAVBZA, Boston; KDKA, Pittsburgh,\nand KYW, Chicago. A large sym\nphony orchestra and a vocal chorus\nof 100 are also on the program.\nHebrew, Russian and German\nsongs will be sung by Cantor Aaron\nKritz tonight at 6 o\u2019clock, Central\ntime, from Station WBBM, Chicago.\nA similar program will be heard at\n8:15 o\u2019clock, Central tiftie from Sta\ntion WMCA, Xew York, which broad\ncasts at that time a \u201cJewish Hour\nof Music and Song.\u201d\nThe Mount Union, O., College Glee\nclub will be a radio entertainer to\nnight with a program at 8 o\u2019clock,\nCentral time, from Station WADC,\nAkron, O.\nA half hour of Irish jigs, reels and\nhornpipes will be given by the Flan\nagan brothers from Station WNYC,\nXew York, at 7 o\u2019clock, Central time,\ntonight.\nString music galore will be on tap\ntonight .from Station WRVA, Rich\nmond. Va., which at 9 o\u2019clock, Cen\ntral time, tonight will broadcast a\nconcert by the East End Mandolin\nclub.\nThe Alleppo Temple Drum corps\nwill again be on the air tonight at\nS o\u2019clock. Central time, from Sta\ntion WBZ, Springfield, Mass.\nSilent Stations\n__MONDAY, APRIL 4.\nCEXTRAL\u2014KLDS, KYW,\nWGES, WHT, WT,S, WJJD,\nWOK. WMAQ, WGN, WLIB,\nWHA8, WQJ, WCFL, WSM.\nEASTERN*\u2014WEBJ, WREO,\nWFI, WIP, WBBR, WEAO,\nWGY.\nFAR WEST\u2014KHJ, KGO.\nWBCN\\\nWOC,\nWEN\u2019R,\nWGBS,\nCFCA,\nBest Features\nMONDAY. APRIL 4.\n(Central Standard Time.)\n6:0# p. m.\nWJZ (450) New York. Roxy and HU\n\nTeaches Over Air\nI\nAlice Keith, shown here, has\nmade possible an extensive music\ncourse for radio listeners.\nBy NE.V Service:\nCLEVELAND, April 3.\u2014One of\nthe most successful applications of\nradio for instruction of students is\nthe music appreciation course\nbroadcast by VTAM of Cleveland in\nco-operation with the Cleveland\nSymphony orchestra and the local\nschools.\nLessons are broadcast on Monday\n\u00a5.nd Wednesday afternoons and are\narranged in a logical study course.\nThe Cleveland orchestra, concerts\nform the baclcobone of the course\nand explanatory talks aid the stu\ndents to understand ami appreciate\nthe music.\nThe talks are concerned with the\ncompositions to be played, com\nposers and instruments used in the\norchestra. There are five symphony\nconcerts during the season and the\nchildren have a better understanding\nof these concerts because of the\ntalks which precede them.\nStarted as Experiment.\nThe system in use in Cleveland is\nthe result of the work of Alice\nKeith, formerly connected with the\neducational department of a large\nphonograph company but now with\nthe Cleveland department of educa\ntion.\nIn Cleveland she realizes the pos\nsibilities of radio and last year\nmade her first experimental broad\ncast of a lesson. The experiment\nwas successful.\nHerbert D. Bixby, superintendent\nof 123 elementary schools in Cleve- j\nland, says of the lessons:\n\u201cThe amount and\u2019 quality of this\neducational material will increase\nand improve so that soon to the\npen and textbook will be added as\nan indispensable tool of the teacher\n\u2014the radio.\u201d\nStudents Are Interested.\nThe climax of the course will be\na music memory contest in which\nall students have an opportunity to\nparticipate. The contest acts as an\nincentive to further interest the stu\ndents in the lessons.\nIt is no longer necessary for the\nstudents to travel to an auditorium\nto hear the symphony concerts as\neach room is equipped with a loud\nspeaker and the talks and programs\nere a part of the regular class room\nwork.\nIn addition to the Cleveland\nschools which benefit by the radio\nmusic course, many schools in small\nneighboring cities have made use of\nthe opportunity offered through\nWTAM and have arranged for their\nstudents to listen in on the entire\nseries.\nGang to chain.\n7:00 p. m.\nWXYO (526) New York. Irish Gigs,\nReels and Hornpipes.\n8:00 p. m.\nWSB (42S.3) Atlanta. \u201cThe Old Home\nTown.\u201d\nWADC (258) Akron. Alt. Union Col\nlege Glee Club.\n8:15 p. m.\nWMAO (311) Now York. Jewish nour\nof .Music.\n9:00 p. m.\nKTHS (374.S) Hot Springs. Folk\nSongs.\nWPG (299.8) Atlantic City. Play, \u201cIn\nHono